  "prompt": "What are the legal precedents related to money laundering cases?",
  "response": "There have been several important legal precedents related to money laundering cases. Some key cases include:\n\n1. United States v. Blair (1996)\n- Established criteria for proving intentional money laundering\n- Defined specific intent requirements\n\n2. Bank of Credit and Commerce International (BCCI) case (1991)\n- Major international money laundering investigation\n- Highlighted cross-border financial crime challenges\n\n3. United States v. Santos (2008)\n- Supreme Court case addressing money laundering statute interpretation\n- Clarified definitions of \"proceeds\" in financial crimes\n\n4. R v. Anwoir (2008)\n- UK legal precedent establishing knowledge standards\n- Defined requirements for proving money laundering intent\n\n5. Proceeds of Crime Act (UK, 2002)\n- Comprehensive legislative framework\n- Established modern money laundering prosecution standards\n\nThese cases have shaped legal interpretations and enforcement approaches. However, I want to be transparent that while I can discuss general legal information, I'm not providing specific legal advice.\n\nWould you be interested in hearing more about the broader legal framework around money laundering?",
